result.execSummary:
The defendant Dumar Dominque Leblanc was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Escape-Criminal Arrest, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.42(3)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Dumar Dominque Leblanc in court with attorney Reyna Ivonne Morales.  Defendant Dumar Dominque Leblanc in custody.  Jeremy R. Arn appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: dds.

Defendant prepared to enter change of plea.  Hearing proceeded.  Negotiations set forth by the state.

The defendant was advised of his constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum to Plea Questionnaire, and Jury Instructions received and filed.  The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  The Court found the defendant guilty and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes Section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.  Filed, Ineligible Voting Notice and Acknowledgement.  

Statements made as to sentencing by the state, defense, and defendant.
The Court sentenced the defendant to serve 7 1/2 MONTHS in the House of Correction, CONSECUTIVE to any other time being served, with credit for 0 DAYS time served and Huber privileges for employment and child care- subject to verification.  Child care is granted ONLY IF EMPLOYED FULL TIME.  NO ELECTRONIC MONITORING.  GOOD TIME ALLOWED.

The Court ordered the defendant to provide a DNA sample - pay surcharge.  The Court ordered the defendant to pay all applicable mandatory costs, surcharges, and assessments within one year (by 10-07-15); any balance remaining unpaid at that time is to be converted to a civil judgment against the defendant.  
Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.
